@module resolver
@lang aria
@layer 2
@aid_version 0.2
@purpose Name resolution, scope hierarchy, and symbol table construction
@depends [lexer, parser, diagnostic]
@workflow The resolver runs after parsing (lexer -> parser -> resolver -> checker -> codegen). It receives the token stream, a DeclIndex of top-level declarations, and a NodePool of AST nodes. It produces a SymbolTable mapping names to scopes and a DiagnosticBag of errors/warnings.
@notes The resolver uses a two-pass design: Pass 1 collects all top-level declarations into the module scope (forward-declaration style), Pass 2 walks function/entry/test bodies to resolve identifier references. This allows mutual recursion between top-level functions without ordering constraints. The resolver operates in a purely functional style -- all state transitions return a new Resolver struct rather than mutating in place.
@antipatterns Do not add symbols during Pass 2 for top-level declarations; they must be registered in Pass 1. Do not resolve identifiers that appear after a dot (field access) -- those are resolved by the checker, not the resolver.

---

@type SymbolKind
@kind sum
@variants
  SkFunction — Function declaration
  SkType — Type declaration (also used for generic type parameters)
  SkEnum — Enum declaration
  SkTrait — Trait declaration
  SkConst — Constant declaration
  SkVariable — Local variable binding (including for-loop vars, with-bindings, destructured names)
  SkParameter — Function parameter (also used for closure params, catch error bindings, ? |e| error bindings)
  SkVariant — Sum type or enum variant
  SkModule — Module name (registered from `use` declarations)
  SkBuiltin — Built-in symbol (types, functions, keywords, constructors)
  SkNone — Sentinel / not found
@source_file src/resolver/scope.aria
@source_line 13
@purpose Classifies what kind of declaration a symbol represents. Used by the resolver to decide whether an identifier in a pattern is a variant constructor (don't bind) or a new variable (bind), and by the checker for type-appropriate validation.
@invariants SkNone is only used as the sentinel value in _sentinel_symbol(); no real declaration should have SkNone.

---

@type ScopeKind
@kind sum
@variants
  ScUniverse — Top-level built-in scope (scope ID 1, contains all builtins)
  ScModule — Module scope (scope ID 2, contains top-level declarations)
  ScFunction — Function body scope (also used for closures, entry blocks, test blocks)
  ScBlock — Block scope (if/for/while/match_arm/catch/select_arm/listcomp/with bodies)
  ScNone — Sentinel (only in _sentinel_scope at index 0)
@source_file src/resolver/scope.aria
@source_line 72
@purpose Classifies scope nesting level for the scope hierarchy. The scope chain always starts with ScNone(0) -> ScUniverse(1) -> ScModule(2) -> user scopes.
@invariants Scope 0 is always the sentinel. Scope 1 is always ScUniverse. Scope 2 is always ScModule. All user-created scopes have ID >= 3.

---

@type Symbol
@kind struct
@fields
  name: str — Symbol name (empty string in sentinel symbol means "not found")
  kind: SymbolKind — Symbol classification
  span: Span — Declaration location (file, line, col, offset, length)
  scope_id: i64 — Scope where declared
  is_mutable: bool — Whether binding is mutable (true only for `mut` bindings)
  is_public: bool — Whether symbol is pub (only meaningful for top-level declarations)
@source_file src/resolver/scope.aria
@source_line 48
@purpose Represents a single named declaration in the symbol table. The sentinel symbol (name="", kind=SkNone) is used as a "not found" return value from lookup functions.
@invariants name="" implies this is the sentinel symbol. scope_id always refers to a valid scope in the SymbolTable.scopes array. is_public is only set for top-level declarations registered in Pass 1.
@notes The span.file field is used for cross-module visibility checking: if a symbol's file differs from the resolver's current file and is_public is false, access is rejected with E0704.

---

@type Scope
@kind struct
@fields
  kind: ScopeKind — Scope classification
  parent: i64 — Parent scope ID (-1 for root, but in practice sentinel at 0 has parent 0)
  name: str — Scope name (function name, "entry", "test", "closure", "for", "match_arm", "catch", "select_arm", "listcomp", or "" for anonymous blocks)
  depth: i64 — Nesting depth (0 for sentinel, computed automatically by add_scope)
@source_file src/resolver/scope.aria
@source_line 89
@purpose Represents a single scope in the scope hierarchy tree. Scopes form a tree via parent pointers, enabling name lookup to walk up the chain.

---

@type SymbolTable
@kind struct
@fields
  scopes: [Scope] — All scopes in hierarchy (index 0 is sentinel)
  symbols: [Symbol] — All declared symbols (index 0 is sentinel)
@source_file src/resolver/scope.aria
@source_line 104
@purpose The resolver's primary output: a complete mapping of all scopes and symbols in the program. Both arrays use index 0 as a sentinel, so real entries start at index 1.
@invariants scopes[0] is always the sentinel scope. symbols[0] is always the sentinel symbol. Both arrays grow monotonically (append-only). Scope IDs and symbol indices are stable once assigned.

---

@type Resolver
@kind struct
@fields
  tokens: [Token] — Token stream from the lexer
  pos: i64 — Current position in the token stream (used by legacy token-walking code)
  table: SymbolTable — Symbol table being built (grows across both passes)
  diagnostics: DiagnosticBag — Accumulated diagnostics (errors and warnings)
  current_scope: i64 — Active scope ID (index into table.scopes)
  file: str — Source file path (used for cross-module visibility checks)
  is_public: bool — Whether current declaration is pub (set during Pass 1 scanning)
  pool: NodePool — AST node pool from the parser (used by AST-based resolution in Pass 2)
  index: DeclIndex — Declaration index from the parser (drives both passes)
@source_file src/resolver/resolver.aria
@source_line 15
@purpose Immutable-style state object threaded through resolution. Every mutation returns a new Resolver with the changed field; the original is never modified.
@notes All _rset_* helper functions create a new Resolver with one field changed. This functional style is required because Aria's bootstrap compiler does not support mutable struct field assignment.
@antipatterns Never mutate the Resolver in place. Always use _rset_* helpers or construct a new Resolver struct.

---

@type ResolveResult
@kind struct
@fields
  table: SymbolTable — Completed symbol table (passed to the checker)
  diagnostics: DiagnosticBag — Resolution diagnostics (merged with checker diagnostics later)
@source_file src/resolver/resolver.aria
@source_line 42
@purpose Return type of the public resolve() function. Packages the final symbol table and any accumulated diagnostics for the next pipeline stage.

